 think I can dynamically write these resources by their names instead of needing to know the jar structure beforehand. ByteBuddyAgent has many inner classes to explore!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering resource loading**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using classloader resources. The `getResourceAsStream` method for the `ByteBuddyAgent` class might work with metadata. I should check if the resource already exists. Also, I wonder if the native resources are just generated from tests. Hmm, maybe that's not quite right. It's probably essential to explore and clarify how these resources can be accessed effectively. I want to ensure I've got the right approach here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering potential exceptions**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the possibility of encountering a `FindException` (RuntimeException) on the JVM if something goes wrong. It seems that a null `codeSource` could indicate a native issue. I might then need to call `Class.forName(\\\"some.generated.Name\\\", true, new URLClassLoader(...))`. I'm also wondering whether using a Native Image could throw an `UnsupportedFeatureError`, but it seems like `URLClassLoader` might not cause that. There’s a lot of nuance here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring dynamic tests**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how native might not reach this case because dynamic tests only catch errors. If it leads to null, it causes an assertion failure. I'm wondering if the compiler could still handle a null call with `MethodHandles.lookup().defineClass(new byte[]{0})`, but it seems like it can't. There's a lot going on here regarding error handling and how null affects the execution flow. It's challenging!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ySBfZ74PiodJ9VKvbRuJsWdu|fc_053aa169fd2341d7016a292f025994819697c97d10569be28a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); mkdir -p \"$tmp/src\"; cat > \"$tmp/src/module-info.java\" <<'EOF'\nmodule blockhound.bytebuddy.ag